<EXM ref="2022.14" paper="2022.14"><EBODY>@{<E>
Prove that the set of components of a topological space forms a
partition of that space.[5]
</E>@}</EBODY><SOLN/>@{<WR>
Let <M>(X,\tau)</M>  be our topological space. We define a binary relation on <M>X</M>  as follows.

For <M>a,b\in X</M>  we shall say <M>a\sim b</M>  if and only if there are no disjoint clopen sets <M>A,B\seq X</M>  with
 <M>a\in A</M>  and <M>b\in B.</M>  

Clearly, this relation is reflexive and symmetric. Also it is transitive.
<BECAUSE>
Let <M>a\sim b</M>  and <M>b\sim c.</M>  Let, if possible, <M>a\not\sim c.</M>

Then there are disjoint  clopen <M>A,C\seq X</M>  with <M>a\in A</M>  and <M>c\in C.</M>

But since <M>a\sim b,</M>  hence <M>b\not\in C.</M>  Also since <M>b\sim c,</M>  hence <M>b\not\in A.</M>  
</BECAUSE>
</WR>@}</EXM>

