<EXM ref="2022.13b" paper="2022.13b"><EBODY>@{<E>
Prove or disprove: Every infinite compact subset of <M>\rr</M> is
connected. Is the converse true? Justify.[3]
</E>@}</EBODY><SOLN/>@{<WR>
Thestatement is false. Counterexample: <M>[0,1]\cup [2,3]</M>  is closed and bounded, and hence compact in <M>\rr</M>  (usual
 topology). Also it is an infinite set. But it is not cononected, as <M>[0,1]</M>  and <M>[2,3]</M>  provide a disconnection.
 
The converse statement is: Every connected subset in <M>\rr</M>  is infinite, compact. 

This is also false. Counterexample: <M>(0,1)</M>  is connected, but not compact. Also <M>\{0\}</M>  is connected, but not
 infinite. 
</WR>@}</EXM>

