@{<WR>
Let the topological space be compact. Take any family <M>{\cal F}=\{F_ \alpha~:~\alpha\in \Lambda\}</M>  with FIP. 
Let, if possible, <M>\cap _{\alpha\in \Lambda} F_ \alpha = \phi.</M>  Then, de Morgan, <M>\cup _{\alpha\in \Lambda} F_ \alpha^c = X.</M> 
 So <M>\{F_ \alpha^c~:~ \alpha\in \Lambda\}</M>  is an open cover of <M>X.</M>

Since <M>X</M>  is compact, there is a finite subcover, <M>\{F_{\alpha_1}^c,...,F_{\alpha_n}^c\}</M>  ie, 
<M>\cup _{i=1}^n F_ \alpha_i^c = X,</M>  ie, <M>\cap _{i=1}^n F_ \alpha_i = \phi (\contra</M>  FIP<M>).</M>

Conversely, if every family with FIP has non-empty intersection, then we shall show that <M>X</M>  must be compact.

Let <M>\{U_ \alpha~:~\alpha\in \Xi\}</M>  be an open cover for <M>X.</M>  Then <M>\cap _{\alpha\in \Xi} U_ \alpha^c = \phi.</M>

Hence <M>\{U_ \alpha^c~:~\alpha\in \Xi\}</M>  cannot have FIP, ie, we have some finite subfamily <M>\{U_{\alpha_1}^c,...,U_{\alpha_n}^c\}</M> 
 with <M>\cap _{i=1}^n U_ {\alpha_i}^c = \phi</M>, ie <M>\cap _{i=1}^n U_ {\alpha_i} = X.</M>

This is a finite subcover of <M>X.</M>
</WR>@}
