Then <M>\tau</M>  is a topology on <M>X.</M>  
<BECAUSE>
Clearly, <M>\phi, X\in\tau.</M>

Let <M>\{U_ \alpha~:~ \alpha\in \Lambda\}\seq \tau.</M>   If <M>\infty</M>  or <M>-\infty</M>  is in some <M>U_ \alpha,</M> 
 then <M>\cup_ {\alpha\in \Lambda} U_ \alpha</M>  one of <M>\{-\infty\}\cup\nn,</M>@}  @{<M>\{\infty\}\cup\nn,</M>  or <M>X.</M> 
 If <M>\infty </M> or <M>-\infty</M>  is not in any of the <M>U_ \alpha</M>'s, then <M>\cup_
 {\alpha\in \Lambda} U_ \alpha\seq \nn.</M>  

Thus, in either case, <M>\cup_ {\alpha\in \Lambda} U_ \alpha\in \tau.</M>

Let <M>U_1,U_2\in\tau.</M>  If <M>U_1, U_2</M>  do not contain <M>\pm\infty,</M>  then <M>U_1\cap U_2\seq\nn.</M>   If <M>U_1 </M> or
 <M>U_2</M>  equals <M>X,</M>  then also done. 

If <M>-\infty\in U_1</M>  
</BECAUSE>
Here <M>K_1 = \{-\infty\}\cup \nn</M>  and <M>K_2 = \{\infty\}\cup \nn</M>  are both compact. Because any cover of <M>K_1</M> 
 must contain <M>K_1</M>  itself. Similarly for <M>K_2.</M>  

But <M>K_1\cap K_2=\nn,</M>  which is not compact, because the open cover <M>{#{~\{n\}~:~n\in\nn~}#}</M>  does not have a
 finite subcover.
</WR>@}</EXM>

